Solutions by Bruce Gray for https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/perl-weekly-challenge-148/

The Raku solution to Task#2 shows four different results for "first 5",
to show the different orderings produced by different algorithms.

Output:
$ perl perl/ch-1.pl
    2 4 6 30 32 34 36 40 42 44 46 50 52 54 56 60 62 64 66
$ raku raku/ch-1.raku
    2 4 6 30 32 34 36 40 42 44 46 50 52 54 56 60 62 64 66

$ perl perl/ch-2.pl 
     2   1   5
     5   1  52
     8   1 189
    11   1 464
    14   1 925
$ raku raku/ch-2.raku
    ((  2   1   5) (  5   2  13) ( 17  18   5) ( 17   9  20) (  8   3  21))
    ((  2   1   5) (  5   2  13) (  8   3  21) ( 17   9  20) ( 17  18   5))
    ((  2   1   5) (  5   1  52) (  5   2  13) (  8   1 189) (  8   3  21))
    ((  2   1   5) (  5   1  52) (  8   1 189) ( 11   1 464) ( 14   1 925))
    

Analysis of Task#2:

If I get a blogpost written, I plan to delve into how `=~=` is insufficient for this task, as the default $*TOLERANCE misses some cases.

Original equation: (a + bâˆšc)^â…“ + (a - bâˆšc)^â…“ = 1
When solved for `c` via https://www.wolframalpha.com/ :
  Solve[ Cbrt[a + bSqrt[c]] + Cbrt[a - bSqrt[c]] = 1, c ]
      c = (a + 1)Â² * (8a - 1) / 27bÂ²
  Useful!
  Also means that:
      (a + 1)Â² * (8a - 1) / 27bÂ²c = 1

# Full derivation:
# https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/2160805/cardano-triplet-transformation
Original equation:
    (a + bâˆšc)^â…“ + (a - bâˆšc)^â…“ = 1
Move 2nd term across:
    (a + bâˆšc)^â…“  = 1 - (a - bâˆšc)^â…“
Cubing just removes the cube-root on the left, and expands on the right to:
    Expand[ (1 - Cbrt[a - bSqrt[c]])Â³ ]
                    3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“)Â² - 3 (a - bâˆšc)^â…“ - a + bâˆšc + 1
     a + bâˆšc == 1 + 3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“)Â² - 3 (a - bâˆšc)^â…“ - a + bâˆšc
     a       == 1 + 3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“)Â² - 3 (a - bâˆšc)^â…“ - a      
    2a       == 1 + 3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“)Â² - 3 (a - bâˆšc)^â…“          
    2a - 1   ==     3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“)Â² - 3 (a - bâˆšc)^â…“
    2a - 1   ==    -3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“) (1 - (a - bâˆšc)^â…“)
Use original equality to substitute the last part from (a-...) to (a+...) :
    2a - 1   ==    -3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“) ((a + bâˆšc)^â…“)
Cube both sides again:
    Expand[ (2a - 1)Â³ ]
        8aÂ³ - 12aÂ² + 6a - 1
    Expand[ (-3 ((a - bâˆšc)^â…“) ((a + bâˆšc)^â…“))Â³ ]
        27bÂ²c - 27aÂ²
    8aÂ³ - 12aÂ² + 6a - 1 == 27bÂ²c - 27aÂ²
    8aÂ³ + 15aÂ² + 6a - 1 == 27bÂ²c
Factor[8aÂ³ + 15aÂ² + 6a - 1]
    (a + 1)Â² (8a - 1) == 27bÂ²c
Now solving for `c` is easy:
    (a + 1)Â² (8a - 1) / 27bÂ² == c
`c` can only be a whole number if (a + 1)Â² (8a - 1) can be evenly divided by 27bÂ².


Jean Marie goes further, in https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/1885095/parametrization-of-cardano-triplet ,
showing (halfway through) that ğ‘ â‰¡ 2 ğ‘šğ‘œğ‘‘ 3. 

Humor:
Easy to prove that, if we lock `b` to always be 1, and `ğ‘ â‰¡ 2 ğ‘šğ‘œğ‘‘ 3` , then `c` will be integer for all `a` generated from 3k+2.
    (a + 1)Â² (8a - 1) / 27 == c
    Expand[((3k + 2) + 1)Â² * (8(3k + 2) - 1)]
        216kÂ² + 567kÂ² + 486k + 135
    Factor[Expand[((3k + 2) + 1)Â² * (8(3k + 2) - 1)]]
        27 (k + 1)Â² (8k + 5)
    Aha! Always divisible by 27!
So, a cheap way to generate Cardano triplets is (3k+2, 1, (k + 1)Â² (8k + 5)) for k=0..Inf.
Since 1 in the lowest possible `b`, using k=0..4 would give a reasonable (although unexpected) answer for the task.
